         </div>
         <div>
            <lb/><head>34) <hi rend="bold">c-minor</hi>.</head>
            <p>Tonic C-major; minor sub-dominant (f-minor) in C-major; use this f-minor, which is
               at the same time the sub-dominant fo c-minor. (Cadence!)</p>
            <p>[C<hi rend="superscript">I</hi>, C<hi rend="superscript">IV</hi><hi
               rend="subscript">&#9837;<!-- ♭, music flat sign --></hi> (= c<hi rend="superscript">IV</hi>), c<hi
                  rend="superscript">V<hi rend="superscript">6</hi><hi rend="subscript"
                     >4</hi></hi>, c<hi rend="superscript">V<hi rend="subscript">&#9838;<!-- ♮, music natural sign --></hi></hi>, | c<hi rend="superscript">I</hi>]</p>
         </div>
         <div type="footer">
            <note xml:id="fn01" type="footnote">*) The Dorian sixth is the major sixth in minor, which must always be led upwards (to the leading tone); for instance, f&#9839;<!-- ♯, music sharp sign--> in a-minor; this f&#9839;<!-- ♯, music sharp sign--> can be taken as the "Third" in D-major and also as the "Fifth" in the b-minor triad! (Hence D-major and b-minor: Chords of the Dorian sixth in a-minor!</note>
         </div>
